import haxe.macro.Expr;

/**
	For some reason... I don't know why... the compiler refuses to allow the existance of anything
	from the `haxe.macro.Type` module. So this is a small hack to bypass the uses of `TypedExpr`.
**/
typedef RTypedExpr = #if (neko || eval || display) haxe.macro.Type.TypedExpr #else Dynamic #end;

/**
	`haxe.macro.Context` loses fields outside of a macro context. This causes issues with IDE usage
	since code needs to be "runtime-compatible", to be used with Visual Studio Code and null-safety
